, rooster’ (or the related byname <i>Cocca</i>) + <i>burna</i> ‘stream’ (see   Bourne  ). This surname is traditionally pronounced <i>Coburn</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Bourne","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived beside a stream, from southern Middle English <i>bourne</i>, Old English <i>burna</i>, <i>burne</i> ‘spring, stream’, or a habitational name from a place called with this word, for example Bourn in Cambridgeshire or Bourne in Lincolnshire. In surnames the reference is often to an old stream called <i>burna</i>, surviving as the name of a farm. This word was replaced as the general word for a stream in southern dialects by Old English <i>brōc</i> (see   Brook  ) and came to be restricted in meaning to a stream flowing only intermittently, especially in winter."]},{"name":"Coburn","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Cockburn  , reflecting the pronunciation.","Altered form of German <b>Kobern</b>."]},{"name":"Cobourn","meanings":["Scottish and English (Staffordshire): variant of   Cockburn  ."]},{"name":"Cogburn","meanings":["English: probably a variant of   Cockburn  ."]}]},{"name":"Piers","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Regular medieval vernacular form of   Peter   (from the Old French nominative case, as against the oblique <i>Pier</i>, modern <i>Pierre</i>). In the form <i>Pierce</i> it survived into the 18th century, although in part this may be a transferred use of the surname derived from the medieval given name. <i>Piers</i> was revived in the mid-20th century, perhaps partly under the influence of  William Langland's  great rambling medieval poem Piers Plowman (  1367–86 ), in which the character of Piers symbolizes the virtues of hard work, honesty, and fairness."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Piers de Cockburn of Henderland was born about 1365, in Henderland, Peeblesshire, Scotland, his father, Piers Cockburn, was 27 and his mother, Marjorie de Soulis or Sules, was 27. He had at least 4 sons and 1 daughter with Helena De Scott. He died in 1418, at the age of 54."},"et":{"about 1365–1418":"umbes 1365–1418","1365–1418":"1365–1418","1370–Female":"1370–Surnud","1394–Male":"1394–Surnud","1397–Male":"1397–Surnud","1402–1463":"1402–1463","1372–Male":"1372–Surnud","1417–1474":"1417–1474","1340–Male":"1340–Surnud","1340–Female":"1340–Surnud","1340":"1340","1372":"1372","1394":"1394","1370":"1370","from about 1372 to 1432":"umbes 1372 kuni 1432","1402":"1402","about 1417":"umbes 1417","1365":"1365","1474":"1474","1463":"1463","1397":"1397","about 1365":"umbes 1365","about 1397":"umbes 1397","1418":"1418","about 1394":"umbes 1394","1417":"1417","Henderland, Peeblesshire, Scotland":"Henderland, Peeblesshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"about 1365–1418":"noin 1365–1418","1365–1418":"1365–1418","1370–Female":"1370–Kuollut","1394–Male":"1394–Kuollut","1397–Male":"1397–Kuollut","1402–1463":"1402–1463","1372–Male":"1372–Kuollut","1417–1474":"1417–1474","1340–Male":"1340–Kuollut","1340–Female":"1340–Kuollut","1340":"1340","1372":"1372","1394":"1394","1370":"1370","from about 1372 to 1432":"vuodesta noin 1372 vuoteen 1432","1402":"1402","about 1417":"noin 1417","1365":"1365","1474":"1474","1463":"1463","1397":"1397","about 1365":"noin 1365","about 1397":"noin 1397","1418":"1418","about 1394":"noin 1394","1417":"1417","Henderland, Peeblesshire, Scotland":"Henderland, Peeblesshire, Scotland"},"fr":{"about 1365–1418":"environ 1365–1418","1365–1418":"1365–1418","1370–Female":"1370–Décédée","1394–Male":"1394–Décédé","1397–Male":"1397–Décédé","1402–1463":"1402–1463","1372–Male":"1372–Décédé","1417–1474":"1417–1474","1340–Male":"1340–Décédé","1340–Female":"1340–Décédée","1340":"1340","1372":"1372","1394":"1394","1370":"1370","from about 1372 to 1432":